						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-assumption-that-a-cow-needs-a-higher-energy-intake-before-calving-challenged" title="The assumption that a cow needs a higher energy intake before calving challenged    " alt="link">The assumption that a cow needs a higher energy intake before calving challenged    </a></h2>

	
					<p>Animal sciences researcher Phil Cardoso and colleagues at the University of Illinois College of Agricultural, Consumer and Environmental Sciences (ACES), conducted &nbsp;an experiment to compare cows fed before calving with diets containing the recommended energy levels (of the US regime) to cows fed only 80% of the recommended &nbsp;energy amount. They found that the cows fed the reduced energy diets performed better reproductively after calving, becoming pregnant about 10 days sooner that cows &nbsp;enjoying the high-energy diet. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<a href="http://www.alphagalileo.org/ViewItem.aspx?ItemId=133665&amp;CultureCode=en" target="_self">http://www.alphagalileo.org/ViewItem.aspx?ItemId=133665&amp;CultureCode=en</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;(AlphaGalileo, 14/08/2013) &nbsp;</p>
							<p><span class="date">20/09/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-assumption-that-a-cow-needs-a-higher-energy-intake-before-calving-challenged">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
